<br>
You obviously havent worked at too many customer service jobs in the past.  People don't post glowing reviews on games usually on boards - they come to boards to bitch or try and get issues fixed.  Same with customer service for say your Cell phone - 99% of the calls are going to be that someone is upset with something wrong, you really think 1000 people a day call them and say damn this phone rocks works all the time.  No - people in general do not do that, so that is the reason you see the posts you do, if people are content they will just sit back and play, if not they will come to boards and post.  <br>
<br>
There are 400,000+ accounts active according to VI - I think that says a lot about how people like the game.  If the game sucked so much or wasn't worth the money people would find other things to do.  $3 a month or less if 3+ month is nothing - almost every online game in existance had price changes in its time.  I played M59 for 2 years and it was more expensive for much less than EQ 4 years ago.  EQ has been competively priced for quite awhile and for that I am glad but to complain about a $3 a month increase after 3 years is dumb.  Other games are charging 12.95 a month for games (according to subscription rates and flocks of people returning to EQ) that are worse.<br>
<br>
On the topic of working on multiple things without fixing bugs - haven't you ever heard of project teams? Too many people working on issues can be a bad thing.  Also, if they fixed every bug in the game and no new content was added for 3 years you think people would stay? Hell no, a lot of people want new content and the high end game is crowded as it is.  Sure, everyone would like to see the Bazaar, new UI, old bugs fixed - but this doesn't need to be the only thing they are working on and if it is they would be an incredibly stupid company.<br>
<br>
At the end though it comes down to how much you are willing to pay.  EQ for the amount of time that many play is the cheapest enterntainment you will find.  Goto a movie with a friend and buy popcorn - guarantee you will spend $12 for 2-3 hours.  Rent a few movies 10-12 dollars.  Spend $40 on a single player game that lasts 10-20 hours. Sure price increases suck but comparable to other forms of enterntainment, this increase isnt anything to get upset about. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uruldarswiftnote.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ruldar Swiftnote</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalWhite.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Wog</span><br>  Posts: 20<br> <font color=#FFFF00>(3/26/02 7:48:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ftherathetravelagencyfrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1150.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Anger</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> As for the comments about me working for AO because I make negative comments about EQ, that is just silly. It is an accepted marketing norm that happy and content consumers are quiet consumers in terms of a public forum, and what you speak of about your Dodge truck is word of mouth praise among your own circle of family and close friends. It is very rare to see public praise for a company or product unless A) The company has gone above and beyond the call of duty, and an overwhelming amount of consumers are happy and excited about the said product/company or B) The person giving praise is being paid to do it, either by the said company in terms of press releases, or by a 3rd party publication who uses reviews and opinions of said produ